'''''Ready''''' is the third [[studio album]] by American [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer [[Trey Songz]]. The album, his first studio release since 2007's ''[[Trey Day]]'', was released by Songbook and [[Atlantic Records]] on August 31, 2009 in the United States. Production for the album began in 2008 and continued until 2009, featuring contributions from Songz's mentor [[Troy Taylor (producer)|Troy Taylor]], [[Bryan-Michael Cox]], [[Stargate (production team)|Stargate]], and [[Los Da Mystro]], among others. 

The album received generally positive reviews from critics. Reviews positively compared ''Ready'' to the work of [[R. Kelly]], but criticized the album's inconsistency. It debuted at number three on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and peaked at number two on the U.S. [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart, selling 131,000 copies in its first week. The album was later certified [[RIAA certification|Gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), becoming Songz's first certified album.

Five singles released from ''Ready'' achieved chart success, including the top ten [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] hit "[[Say Aah]]", and the top five [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] hits "[[Neighbors Know My Name]]" and "[[I Invented Sex]]", the latter of which topped the chart. Songz promoted ''Ready'' in a number of live appearances, including co-heading the 106 & Live tour, sponsored by ''[[106 & Park]]'', and serving as a support act on [[Jay-Z]]'s [[The Blueprint 3 Tour]]. ''Ready'' earned Songz a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Best Contemporary R&B Album]] at the [[52nd Grammy Awards]]; however, it lost to [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]]' ''[[I Am...Sasha Fierce]]''.

==Production and development==
When Songz began recording for ''Ready'', the purpose of the album was to crossover and increase his exposure on radio. The album's lead single, "I Need a Girl", was released to connect to mainstream radio. Songz said that "[it] was a very radio-geared record which would do great and play on radio heavily during whatever time. It wasn't a record I expected to last forever, or one I was even excited about singing, but it was a record I knew would do well." Speaking of the following singles, Songz thought that "I Invented Sex" would be a "career-defining record, and I knew 'Say Aah' would be a monster club record."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expressnightout.com/content/2010/09/trey-songz-monica-passion-pain-pleasure-dar-constitution-hall.php |title=Songz For Hot Summer Nightz: Trey Songz, ''Passion, Pain & Pleasure,'' at DAR Constitution Hall |author=Hadadi, Roxana |date=2010-09-02 |work=[[Express (newspaper)|Express]] |accessdate=2010-09-05}} </ref>

Production began in late 2008 and was completed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://emusician.com/remixmag/artists_interviews/musicians/wizard-oz-bryan-michael-cox/ |title=Wizard of Oz: Bryan-Michael Cox |author=Micallef, Ken |date=2008-11-01 |work=[[Electronic Musician]] |accessdate=2010-09-03}}</ref> The album features production from [[Stargate (production team)|Stargate]], [[Johnt<U+00E1> Austin]], [[Troy Taylor (producer)|Troy Taylor]], [[Los Da Mystro]], [[Eric Hudson]] and [[Bryan-Michael Cox]]. Speaking on his collaborations with the producers, Songz said that on ''Ready'', "we're breaking down every song, every hook, every chorus, every bridge, and we're making sure every song is the best song it could be. This album isn't just going to be a compilation of songs, but a classic body of work."<ref name="Billboardfeature">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/trey-songz-ready-to-grow-up-on-third-album-1003999310.story|title=Trey Songz 'Ready' To Grow Up On Third Album|first=Mariel|last=Concepcion|date=2009-07-31|accessdate=2010-07-04|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.}}</ref> The album originally contained three guest features, [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]], [[Gucci Mane]] and [[Soulja Boy Tell 'Em]].<ref name="Billboardfeature"/> Songz wanted to keep the amount of features very limited, and stated that "anybody else I add is going to be very special".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagodefender.com/article-4614-singer-trey-songz-is-ready-to-get-back-to-business.html |title=Singer Trey Songz is 'Ready' to get back to business |author=Vaughn, Shamontiel L. |date=2009-05-22 |work=[[Chicago Defender]] |accessdate=2010-09-05}}</ref> [[Fabolous]] was later added as a guest feature on "Say Aah".

Songz said that compared to his previous albums, "this album is very adult, very easygoing and very sexy [...] My first album was very adult-like, but in a different, more soulful, sample-driven kind of way, and my second one was more contemporary and trendy." To reflect his transition into adulthood and the changes in his music, Songz changed his appearance by cutting of his trademark braids.<ref name="Billboardfeature"/> Songz also began dressing in more sophisticated attire, trading in sneakers and T-shirts for vests, tailored pants, and "tasteful" shoes.<ref name="Aparticle"/> On the appearance change, Songz's mentor, producer, and the head of Songbook Entertainment, [[Troy Taylor (producer)|Troy Taylor]] said, "Trey's from the streets, he's a [[Ghetto|hood]] kid. He wasn't glamorous and (didn't have) the finer things in life growing up, [...] He didn't want to lose his [[Credibility|street-ism]], [...] As he grew into it I think he began to realize, 'Wait a minute, this ain't that bad after all,' and then he got the ladies' opinions."<ref name="Aparticle">{{cite web|url=http://www.treysongz.com/news/ap-rb-crooner-trey-songz-is-ready-for-the-world/|title=AP: R&B crooner Trey Songz is ready for the world|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Atlantic Records]]/Trey Songz.com|accessdate=2010-07-04|date=2010-01-22}}</ref>

The album was originally set to be released on June 30, 2009; however, Songz delayed the date to September 1, 2009 so that he could return to the studio and finish the album. The release date was then moved up one day to August 31, 2009, in order for the album's work to be considered for the [[2010 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treysongz.com/news/trey-songz-interview-with-gowherehiphopcom/|title=Trey Songz Interview With GoWhereHipHop.com|date=2009-08-27|accessdate=2010-07-05|publisher=TreySongz.com, [[Atlantic Records]]}}</ref>

After ''Ready''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s success, Songz explained that the album was a result of his growth and new-found maturity.<ref name="Definitive">{{cite web|url=http://www.singersroom.com/news/5451/Trey-Songz-Calls-Ready-Definitive-Album|title=Trey Songz Calls Ready 'Definitive' Album|publisher=Singersroom|date=2010-03-07|accessdate=2010-07-05}}</ref> Commenting about the success of his singles, Songz stated that "they're very strong records and they're not just radio records. They're records that embody the person I am as well as the artist I am. I think they're more definitive of who I am than any other album I've had. I've grown as an artist. I've been doing this for awhile now. As I've matured, I've learned how to exude that of which I want to be felt. I've learned what my fans want from me and things of that nature."<ref name="Definitive"/>

==Composition==
{{Listen
 |pos          = right
 |filename     = Sayaah.ogg
 |title        = "Say Aah"
 |description  = Songz's first top ten hit is [[electronica]]-driven [[hip-hop]]. 
 |filename2    = Neighborsknowmyname.ogg
 |title2       = "Neighbors Know My Name"
 |description2 = The album's fifth single, which contains a "knocking bassline." 
}}
The album contains influences of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[hip hop music|hip-hop]] and [[pop music|pop]], with a bit of [[soul music|soul]], as much of the work has been compared to vintage [[R. Kelly]].<ref name="USAtoday"/><ref name="Allmusic"/> Concerning the album's lyrical content, Ken Capobianco of the ''[[Boston Globe]]'' said, "While many male modern R&B vocalists are moving to a more mature vibe, Trey Songz keeps the horndog-with-a-heart tradition alive with his third album."<ref name="Bostonglobe">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/cd_reviews/articles/2009/08/31/trey_songz_ready/|title=Trey Songz, 'Ready'|date=2009-08-31|accessdate=2010-07-03|first=Ken|last=Capobianco|work=[[Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Sean Fennessey of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' said, that ''Ready'', featured Songz's "re-imagining the notion of flow<U+2014>if not melody<U+2014>just as his hero Kelly did 15 years ago."<ref name="VillageVoice"/> Andrew Rennie of ''[[NOW Magazine]]'' said the production had an 80's soundtrack vibe.<ref name="Nowmagazine"/> According to Mark Edward Nero of [[About.com]], "I Need A Girl" contains familiar qualities of Songz's breakout hit "[[Can't Help But Wait]]", also produced by Stargate.<ref name="Aboutreview"/> The song is lyrically about finding and pleasing the right woman.<ref name="Aboutreview"/> The song has also been described to be a mix of [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]] and [[Justin Timberlake]]<ref name="Newsday"/> Melanie Bertoli of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said that "Neighbors Know My Name" "employs a knocking bassline and drip-drop effect to provide the ideal erotic backdrop for Songz's dirty talk."<ref name="BILLBOARDREVIEW">{{cite web|url=ite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/new-releases/trey-songz-neighbors-know-my-name-1004080362.story#/new-releases/trey-songz-neighbors-know-my-name-1004080362.story|title=Trey Songz, "Neighbors Know My Name"|date=2010-04-02|accessdate=2010-04-23|first=Melanie|last=Bertoli|work=''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''}}</ref> "[[Say Aah]]" is an [[electrohop]] piece about a birthday celebration, said to rival "[[Birthday Sex]]", and "[[Blame It]]."<ref name="vibe">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/mt/2009/12/singled-out-trey-songz-feat-young-jeezy-say-aah-remix|title=Singled Out: Trey Songz Feat. Young Jeezy "Say Aah (Remix)" |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|author=jkennedy|accessdate=2010-07-05|date=2009-12-12}}</ref> "Black Roses" is "set to quasi-electronica production, buoyed by a soulful vocal arrangement."<ref name="Popmatters"/> Tyler Lewis of ''[[PopMatters]]'' said "Be Where You Are" was reminiscent of [[Jordan Knight]]'s "[[Give It to You (Jordan Knight song)|Give It to You]]", and called it Songz's purest pop song to date.<ref name="Popmatters"/>"Yo Side of the Bed", containing soul influences, has been called R&B-[[pop rock]] similar to some of [[Beyonce]]'s work on ''[[I Am...Sasha Fierce]]'' and [[Brandy (entertainer)|Brandy]] on ''[[Human (Brandy Norwood album)|Human]]''.<ref name="USAtoday"/><ref name="Popmatters"/> "LOL Smiley Face" is lyrically about [[sexting]], while featuring a "ringtone-ready" chorus, and heavy percussion.<ref name="Tinymixtapes"/>

==Promotion==
To promote the album, a major online campaign was launched, his blog site, SeeFurtherThanIAm.com, on which Songz streams live chats and behind-the-scenes videos.<ref name="Billboardfeature"/> He also released a track on his [[Twitter]] every Monday, some of which were from his mixtape ''Anticipation'', which preceded the album's release.<ref name="Billboardfeature"/> Songz embarked on a promo tour on July 25, 2009, with stops in [[Chicago]], [[Miami]], [[Atlanta]], [[Dallas]] and [[the Carolinas]], where he attended radio events and listening sessions.<ref name="Billboardfeature"/> He also toured the [[House of Blues]] in September, as well as a college tour also that fall.<ref name="Billboardfeature"/> In addition to co-headlining the [[106 & Park|106 & Live!]] tour with [[Mario Barrett|Mario]], also featuring [[Day26]] and [[Sean Garrett]], which toured from September 29 to October 31, 2009, Songz's served as a supporting act in 2010 for [[Jay-Z]]'s [[The Blueprint 3 Tour]], along with [[Young Jeezy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1622612/20090929/trey_songz.jhtml|title=Trey Songz Talks His First Headlining Tour, Which Launches Today|first=Hillary|last=Crosley|date=2009-09-29|accessdate=2010-07-04|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=MTV Networks}}</ref>  

In addition to the online and touring promotion, Songz made an appearance with his mother and younger-half brother, Forrest, to perform at ''AMBER Ready Back-to-School Safety Weekend at ABC Studios'' in [[Times Square]] on August 16, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treysongz.com/news/trey-amber-readys-back-2-school-weekend/|title=Trey @ AMBER Ready's Back 2 School Weekend!|publisher=TreySongz.com, [[Atlantic Records]]|accessdate=2010-07-04|date=2009-08-17}}</ref> He appeared on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s ''[[106 & Park]]'' on August 31, September 1, and September 2, 2009, performing a medley of "[[Successful (song)|Successful]]", "[[I Need a Girl (Trey Songz song)|I Need a Girl]]" and "[[LOL Smiley Face]]" on the latter date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treysongz.com/news/successful-video-to-premiere-on-monday-831-on-mtv/|title="Successful" Video to Premiere on Monday, 8/31 on MTV!|publisher=TreySongz.com, [[Atlantic Records]]|date=2009-08-24|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref> He performed "I Need a Girl" on September 9, 2009 on ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treysongz.com/news/trey-to-perform-on-wendy-williams-tomorrow/|title=Trey to Perform on Wendy Williams Tomorrow!|date=2009-09-08|publisher=TreySongz.com, [[Atlantic Records]]}}</ref>

==Singles==
The album's first single "[[I Need a Girl (Trey Songz song)|I Need a Girl]]" was released as the [[lead single]] via [[music download|digital download]] on April 13, 2009, with "Brand New" as its [[B-side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/I-Need-Girl-Brand-New/dp/B0026E2AN8|title=Amazon.com: I Need A Girl / Brand New|accessdate=2010-07-06|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref> "I Need A Girl" received positive to mixed reviews, with some critics comparing it to "[[Can't Help But Wait]]" and others noting it as generic.<ref name="Aboutreview">{{cite web|url=http://randb.about.com/od/reviews/fr/TreySongzReady.htm|title=Trey Songz - 'Ready'|first=Mark Edward|last=Nero|accessdate=2010-07-02|publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref> The song peaked at fifty-nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and six on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]].<ref name="Songz">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/trey-songz/640724|title=Trey Songz Music News & Info - Billboard.com|work=''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|accessdate=2010-07-06}}</ref> Songz appeared as a featured artist on [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]]'s single, "[[Successful (song)|Successful]]", which peaked at seventeen on the Hot 100, and was a success on other charts, reaching three and two, respectively, on the R&B/Hip-Hop and [[Rap Songs]] charts. Although it was not released as a dual single for Songz and Drake, Songz included it on ''Ready'', sans the other featured guest, [[Lil Wayne]]'s verse, and the addition of another by himself.<ref name="Nicki">{{cite web|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2009/08/31/trey-songz-talks-lack-of-accolades-collabo-album-with-drake-possible-lol-remix/|title=Trey Songz Talks Lack of Accolades, Collabo Album With Drake & Possible <U+2018>LOL<U+2019> Remix|first=Carl|last=Lamarre|date=2009-08-31|accessdate=2010-07-04|publisher=BallerStatus.com}}</ref> "[[LOL Smiley Face]]", featuring rappers [[Gucci Mane]] and [[Soulja Boy Tell 'Em]] was released to airplay as the album's second single on August 24, 2009.<ref name="Radio1">{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=08/25/2009&Format=5|title=R&R - Going for Adds|publisher=R&R|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref> The song received generally positive reviews, while peaking at fifty-one on the Hot 100.<ref name="Tinymixtapes">{{cite web|url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/trey-songz-ready|title=Trey Songz|first=Ajitpaul|last=Mangat|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref><ref name="Songz"/>

"[[I Invented Sex]]", featuring Drake, was released to airplay as the album's third single on October 13, 2009.<ref name="Radio2">{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/12/2009&Format=5|title=R&R Going for Adds - Urban - Week Of: October 13, 2009|publisher=RadioandRecords|accessdate=2010-07-06}}</ref> While reaching forty-two on the Hot 100, it became Songz's first number one hit on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart.<ref name="Songz"/> The song was accompanied by an official remix featuring fellow R&B singers [[Keri Hilson]] and [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2009/12/07/new-music-trey-songz-f-usher-keri-hilson-i-invented-sex-remix/|title=New Music: Trey Songz f/ Usher & Keri Hilson <U+2013> <U+2018>I Invented Sex (Remix)<U+2019>|work=[[Rap-Up]]|accessdate=2010-09-05|date=2009-12-07}}</ref> "[[Say Aah]]", an [[electrohop]] song about a birthday celebration, was the album's fourth single, and became the most successful song of Songz's career, reaching nine on the Hot 100.<ref name="Songz"/> Additionally it was his first song to impact [[contemporary hit radio|pop]] radio, appearing on the [[Pop Songs]] chart, and his first to chart internationally, charting on the [[Canadian Hot 100]].<ref name="Songz"/> "[[Neighbors Know My Name]]" was the album's fifth and final single, and it received generally positive reviews, whilst reaching forty-three on the Hot 100, and four on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs, giving Songz his third consecutive top five single and fifth top ten single from ''Ready''.<ref name="Songz"/> Although not released as a single, a music video for "Yo Side of the Bed", in which Keri Hilson portrayed Songz's love interest, was filmed and released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2010/05/26/video-trey-songz-f-keri-hilson-yo-side-of-the-bed/|title=Video: Trey Songz f/ Keri Hilson <U+2013> <U+2018>Yo Side of the Bed<U+2019>|accessdate=2010-07-07|work=[[Rap-Up]]}}</ref>

==Reception==
===Commercial response===
The album debuted at number three on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with first-week sales of 131,000 copies.<ref name="debut">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/whitney-houston-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-1004010124.story|title=Whitney Houston Debuts At No. 1 On Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|date=2009-09-09|accessdate=2010-07-07}}</ref> ''Ready'' was the second-highest debut of the week only behind [[Whitney Houston]]'s comeback album, ''[[I Look To You]]''.<ref name="debut"/> The album currently remains on the top half of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref name="bbcharts">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/trey-songz/640724#/artist/trey-songz/chart-history/640724?f=305&g=Albums|title=Chart History - Trey Songz: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref>  On February 16, 2010, the album was certified [[RIAA certification|gold]] in sales by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], following shipments in excess of 500,000 copies in the U.S.<ref name="RIAA">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Trey%20Songz&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|title=Gold & Platinum - Searchable Database: ''Ready''|work=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref> It is Songz's first [[RIAA certification|RIAA-certified]] album.<ref name="Gold"/>

