The album received positive reviews from most music critics, receiving an aggregate score of 67 out of 100 from website [[Metacritic]], which indicates "generally favorable reviews."<ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/treysongz/ready|title=Ready reviews at Metacritic.com|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2010-07-07}}</ref> It received many comparisons to the work of R&B artist [[R. Kelly]], while several critics noted it as inconsistent. David Jeffries of [[Allmusic]] said that "Even at a whopping 17 like-minded tracks, all-night lovers wouldn't be caught dead complaining about how overly long it all is", commenting that ''Ready'' "is as entertaining and frivolous as a one-night stand should be."<ref name="Allmusic">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:avfixzy0ldhe~T1|title=allmusic ((( Ready > Review )))|first=David|last=Jeffries|accessdate=2010-07-03|work=[[Allmusic]]}}</ref> Ken Capobianco of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' said that Songz had developed as a vocalist stating, "more elastic and uses his falsetto judiciously".<ref name="Bostonglobe"/> Capobianco commended tracks like "Be Where You Are," and "Love Lost", commenting that "tracks like that show that he is indeed ready for the next step."<ref name="Bostonglobe"/> Andrew Rennie of ''[[Now (magazine)|NOW]]'' said, "slight deviations from R&B<U+2019>s classic formula allow Trey Songz wiggle room to play with his multi-octave voice. This offering sets him apart from other acts and may secure his spot in the canon of bedroom crooners."<ref name="Nowmagazine">{{cite web|url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/music/discs.cfm?content=171297|title=NOW Magazine // Music // Trey Songz|accessdate=2010-07-03|first=Andrew|last=Rennie|work=[[Now (magazine)|NOW]]}}</ref> Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsday]]'' said that after making his name for singing hooks on rap songs, that he "shows his smooth R&B vocals can hold the spotlight all on their own."<ref name="Newsday">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/trey-songz-is-ready-with-smooth-r-b-1.1402139|title=Trey Songz is 'Ready' with smooth R&B|date=2009-08-31|first=Glenn|last=Gamboa|accessdate=2010-07-03|work=[[Newsday]]}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album 3<U+00BD> out of 5 stars and wrote that Songz "takes cues from R. Kelly, slyly mocking the self-parodying excesses of boudoir R&B while supplying the utilitarian goods: the sumptuous vocal harmonies and sultry beats upon which long nights beneath ceiling mirrors depend".<ref name="Metacritic"/> ''[[USA Today]]'' said the album reflects his broad appeal, and that Songz's proves "he's comfortable as a rogue or romantic. Even though the review pointed out that "he occasionally falls back on booty-call clich<U+00E9>s," that "his song craft shines on the edgy "Black Roses" and regretful "Lost Love."<ref name="Usatoday">{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2009-08-31-listen-up-chevelle_N.htm|title=Listen Up: Chevelle's 'Sci-Fi Crimes' is arresting rock 'n' roll |date=2009-09-01|accessdate=2010-07-03|work=[[USA Today]] | first1=Brian | last1=Mansfield | first2=Jerry | last2=Shriver | first3=Steve | last3=Jones | first4=Edna | last4=Gundersen}}</ref> Jon Caramanica of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said, "'Ready' is one of the year<U+2019>s most promising R&B albums, and a curious one at that", commenting, "the results are bawdy but never lecherous; sometimes all his enthusiastic bedroom talk has an air of childlike goofiness to it, as if he were thrilled to get away with boasting so freely."<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/03/arts/music/03highline.html?_r=2|title=He May Not Have Invented Sex, but He Sure Does Like to Sing About It |first=Jon|last=Caramanica|date=2009-09-02|accessdate=2010-07-03|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Sean Fennesssy of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' called the album "one of the year's best.."<ref name="VillageVoice">{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-09-29/music/the-almost-40-year-old-sex-fiend-ghostface-killah/|title=The (Almost)-40-Year-Old Sex Fiend: Ghostface Killah|first=Sean|last=Fennessey|date=2009-09-29|accessdate=2010-07-03|work=[[The Village Voice]]}}</ref> 

Despite viewing it imperfect and noting Songz had not mastered the balancing act "between being a horny boy and ladies' man", Mark Edward Nero of [[About.com]] said it was the best album of Songz's career, commenting, "Trey takes a big step toward establishing himself as an A-list singer."<ref name="Aboutreview"/> Nero also commended consistent vocals as a plus, and complimented the eclecticity of the songs, saying no tracks are unlistenable.<ref name="Aboutreview"/> Tyler Lewis of [[PopMatters]] said that Songz continued his tradition of inconsistent albums, commenting that the album's best is when it departs from the [[R. Kelly]] template.<ref name="Popmatters">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/110659-trey-songz-ready/|title=Trey Songz: Ready|date=2009-09-10|first=Tyler|last=Lewis|accessdate=2010-07-03|work=[[PopMatters]]}}</ref> Lewis recommended that the album needed to be trimmed down and included with some from his mixtape ''Anticipation'' for what could have been, "the black pop record of the year."<ref name="Popmatters"/> Ajitpaul Mangat of [[Tiny Mix Tapes]] called the album often "generic" and "monotonous" noting how Songz's work on freestyles and work ethic proves how the album could be better.<ref name="Tinymixtapes"/> Mangat did overall compliment the album, "While Ready is far from a perfect album, it seems Trey is learning how to inspirit his original works with the charm and inventiveness found in his freestyles and covers."<ref name="Tinymixtapes"/> The album earned Songz a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Best Contemporary R&B Album]] in 2010.<ref name="Gold">[http://www.hiphoppress.com/2010/02/trey-songz-ready-certified-gold-as-he-prepares-to-accompany-jayz-on-his-coasttocoast-bp3-tour-2010.html Trey Songz's "READY" Certified Gold as He Prepares to Accompany Jay-Z on His Coast-to-Coast "BP3 Tour 2010"]. HipHopPress. Retrieved on 2010-05-30.</ref>

